<P>
WORLD CUP USA '94 / THE FIRST ROUND; SPOTLIGHT; MAYBE A REAL DAWN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By IAN RIDLEY, Independent in London 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 "It was a riveting first week to encourage optimism that this might be a 
tournament to banish the sackcloth and ashes of Italia '90 and begin, whisper 
it, to recall the sun-kissed delight that memory insists was Mexico '70. 
</P>
<P>
 "These finals went further -- 16 matches -- without a goal-less draw than any 
since 1958. . . . One hesitates to be so effusive so early, having witnessed so 
many false dawns. Perhaps we are over-eager to escape the negativity that has 
characterized major football for so long. But we may be, just may be, 
privileged to be in on the beginning of the global game rediscovering itself." 
</P>
</TEXT>
