<HEADLINE>
<P>
OFF THE TICKER: A HONEYMOON IN CYBERSPACE? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Something old, something new, something borrowed, something high-tech: That's 
the formula for Cassandra Lehman and Chris Thorne's wedding. The Silicon Valley 
couple will marry Thursday via videoconference, saying their vows to each other 
in New York and to a judge in California. 
</P>
<P>
 The techno-rite is a natural for the pair. Lehman, 29, teaches computer art at 
a university, and Thorne, 34, is president of a firm that sets up audiovisual 
displays for other companies. 
</P>
<P>
 The New York setting for the ceremony will be a computer trade show. If the 
sight of her walking among the expo's booths in a wedding dress doesn't turn 
heads, the accordionist might. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's all really part of our lives, but the ceremony remains the same," Lehman 
said. "We wouldn't do this if it wasn't fun." 
</P>
