said it will have fewer flight attendants on some of its shortest flights 
starting Sept. 1. No layoffs are expected from the changes, and all flights 
will still meet Federal Aviation Administration requirements, said Todd Clay, a 
spokesman for Delta Air Lines Inc. The airline expects to save $17 million a 
year from the changes, with a goal of cutting annual operating costs by about 
$2 billion by June, 1997. 
